    Authoring rules honored (per AAP Sections 0.7.1 / 0.7.2 and the
    agent prompt's ten authoring rules):

      Rule 1 - Synthetic only (AAP Section 0.7.2 NO-PII clause):
        subject       = "Demo case 05: Resolved (General Inquiry)"
        description   = "Synthetic Resolved case awaiting manager
                         close." (no PII; the wording emphasizes the
                         lifecycle position - resolved by agent,
                         awaiting manager review for closure)
        requester_name  = "Synthetic Requester Five" (synthetic
                          identifier using the literal word "Synthetic"
                          plus a numeral spelled out for the requester,
                          NOT a real person's name; consistent with the
                          peer convention used by cases 06, 07, 08, 09,
                          10 - SPELLED-OUT word for the requester_name)
        requester_email = "requester-5@example.invalid"
                          (RFC 2606 / BCP 32 reserved .invalid TLD never
                          resolves to a real domain; the local part uses
                          the NUMERAL "5" matching the file numbering -
                          consistent with the peer convention used by
                          cases 06-10's NUMERAL convention for the email
                          local part versus the SPELLED-OUT word for
                          the requester_name field)

      Rule 2 - No auto-number override:
        The <number/> element is intentionally absent. The auto-number
        engine defined in ../../numbers/sys_number_x_casemgmt_case.xml
        generates a CASE0000001-format value on insert per AAP Section
        0.5.7 (the "number" row of the case schema specifies "Auto-
        number" with format CASE0000001 and Read-only constraint).

      Rule 3 - Auto-set opened_date (NO explicit override):
        The <opened_date/> element is intentionally absent. The
        set_opened_date Before-Insert business rule at
        ../../business_rules/x_casemgmt_set_opened_date.xml fires on
        insert and sets opened_date = gs.nowDateTime(). This means the
        case will appear as "opened today" at import time, which is
        appropriate for the cases_opened_30d widget (this case is
        included in the 30-day count). Unlike case 06 (Closed General
        Inquiry) and case 10 (Closed Complaint) - which DO carry
        explicit opened_date and closed_date overrides because they
        are inputs to the avg_time_to_close widget that filters on
        status=Closed - this case does NOT need an explicit
        opened_date override because:
          * It is NOT used to compute avg_time_to_close (which excludes
            non-Closed cases via the closed_date IS NOT NULL filter).
          * It IS appropriate for the case to appear "fresh" in the
            cases_opened_30d count (a Resolved-but-not-yet-Closed case
            is still recently active).
        Pattern matches case 09 (Resolved Complaint), the Complaint-
        flow analog of this case.

      Rule 4 - No closed_date in Resolved (NO explicit override, NO BR
               fire either):
        The <closed_date/> element is intentionally absent. Per AAP
        Section 0.5.5 the set_closed_date business rule fires only on
        Resolved -> Closed update, NOT on direct insert with status =
        Resolved. So closed_date remains null after insert - which is
        correct for a Resolved (not yet Closed) case. The
        avg_time_to_close report filters on status=Closed and ignores
        null closed_date values, so this case correctly does NOT appear
        in that widget. If/when the demo manager subsequently closes
        this case via the form (which exercises the Resolved -> Closed
        transition path through the validate_closed_transition subflow),
        the set_closed_date Before-Update business rule will fire AT
        THAT TIME and populate closed_date.

